    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>What Would the Founders Say?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jack D Spiro letter on Michael Novak's Sept 4 article cites rights of nonbelievers</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Michael Novak informs us (Op-Ed, Sept. 4) that American Jews, Christians and Muslims concur with the religious language of the Declaration of Independence -- that God is ''Creator, Judge and Providence.'' That leaves, he says, ''perhaps 8 percent'' of Americans who don't believe in this concept of divinity.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Michael Novak informs us (Op-Ed, Sept. 4) that American Jews, Christians and Muslims concur with the religious language of the Declaration of Independence -- that God is ''Creator, Judge and Providence.'' That leaves, he says, ''perhaps 8 percent'' of Americans who don't believe in this concept of divinity.</p>
        <p>Mr. Novak focuses mainly on  the Declaration of Independence, but the Constitution, through the judiciary branch, guarantees protection  for the minority of Americans from the tyranny of the majority. The Constitution does not mention a percentage.</p>
        <p>JACK D. SPIRO  Richmond, Va., Sept. 4, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is director of the Center for Judaic Studies, Virginia Commonwealth University.</p>
      </block>
